All the associations corresponding to anti-viral drugs clinically shown to act against human host viruses have been assembled from standard DrugBank database [55] ( https://www.drugbank.ca/categories/DBCAT000066 ).

ViPR or NIAID Virus Pathogen Database and Analysis Resource ( http://www.viprbrc.org/ ) is a repository of data and analysis tools for virology research [43] capturing various types of information derived from comparative genomics analysis and visualization tools.
It has antiviral drug information (for 21 viral species) derived imported from DrugBank (https://www.drugbank.ca/ ) [55].

The DrugBank Identier (DrugBank ID) of the anti-viral drugs involved is considered as the unique key for the drugs, obtained from DrugBank vocabulary ( https://www.drugbank.ca/releases/latest#open-data ).

Apart from this, each drug is mapped to its corresponding KEGG Identi- er (KEGG ID) from the KEGG Compound/KEGG Drug database ( https://www.genome.jp/kegg/drug/ ,https: //www.genome.jp/kegg/compound/ ) of the KEGG (Kyoto encyclopedia of genes and genomes) [32].
The KEGG IDs were taken from the linking le provided at https://www.drugbank.ca/releases/latest#external-links [55] or manually added in the case of drugs missing in the linking le.

The viral family, genome type, transmission route and incubation period is also available in the virus metadata le along with the accession number of the complete genomic sequence of the viruses fetched from NCBI (National Center for Biotechnology Information) Viral genome browser https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/genomes/GenomesGroup.cgi [1]).

The chemical structure similarity was measured between the drugs by computing the SIMCOMP score [26] based on the maximum common substructures between the chemical structure of the compounds using the KEGG API page at GenomeNet ( https://www.genome.jp/tools/gn_tools_api.
The reference sequences of viruses were saved in FASTA format to be used by the distance computation software ( https://github.com/jessieren/VirHostMatcher ) proposed by [5].
